        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We wish to map the polarization in the core region of NGC1068. This region should show the transition from the disk, dominated by accretion, and the outflow region, and we expect to see the polarization closest to the nucleus perpendicular to that further out in the outflow region (aliged at PA ~60). We therefore need to obtain multiple resolution elements across this region, which has a total continuum flux density of ~60mJy spread over ~1.5-arcsec^2 from the archival band-7 observations in 2011.0.00061.S (Figure 2). 

Based on protostars and star forming regions in our galaxy, we expect the polarized signal to be ~2% (possibly higher where the magnetic field is amplified in the outflow region). Thus we expect the total polarized flux density to be 1.2mJy. With a 0.35" resolution beam we will measure a mean of 0.1mJy/beam of polarized flux, detectable at 5-sigma in 1.7hr of on-source time, and a total time (according to the OT) of 4.09hr, above the 3hr minimum for polarization. (Note that a 5-sigma detection is required as Ricean bias means that lower sigma detections may not be reliable.) NGC1068 has ample flux to self-calibrate, so dynamic range will not be an issue.

Our team has much experience with dealing with polarimetric data, and has the expertise to make the most of this new observing mode, which will require careful calibration and imaging.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
