    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The polarization of thermal dust emission can be used to deduce the orientation of magnetic field
lines in the interstellar medium, and hence the flow patterns of material in regions where molecular line emission is absent. This phenomenon has been exploited in studies of protostars, but, until the advent of ALMA, studies of AGN have been too difficult due to the combination of low spatial resolution and poor sensitivity of previous telescopes. In this proposal, we wish to image the nucleus of the bright nearby Seyfert galaxy NGC1068 in polarized light. By doing so, we will make the first detailed map of the magnetic field properties in the nuclear region of an AGN. We expect to find evidence of both inflow and outflow of material traced by the magnetic field lines which thread the dusty nuclear medium. If successful, this observation will pave the way for a study of a sample of local AGNs with full ALMA.</prp:abstract>
